  <span id="freeText12242243744186668811" style="display:none"><i>
  <blockquote>She went to bed with men as frequently as she could. It was the only place where she could find what she was looking for: misery and the ability to feel deep sorrow. She had not always been aware that it was sadness she yearned for.</blockquote>
</i><br />How does Toni Morrison do that? I read this thinking 'oh, that looks forward to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6149.Beloved" title="Beloved by Toni Morrison" rel="nofollow noopener">Beloved</a>, and that does, too', and the story is drawn-out with a year-by-year structure, and there are so many characters, some mere walk-ons, but this isn't quite a family saga or a portrait of a community - and then I reach the end, and wham! the Morrison magic has clearly been subliminal because somehow she has excavated so much emotion <i>without me even realising it</i> so that by the last line, I just want to weep! <br /><br />So this is one, I'd suggest, where the blurb only barely scratches the surface of the book. The relationship between Nel and Sula doesn't really occupy the centre of the text (though it does turn out to be crucial - just not in the way I'd expected going in); and Sula is an enigmatic figure (yes, she surely looks forward to Beloved?) who we don't wholly understand. <br /><br />But Morrison's emotional imagination is evident, and her writing already beautifully resonant - she might still be learning some of her craft but the potential for greatness is already clear to see.</span>
